<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06157286 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06157286 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  EAST-PALO-ALTO; SCHOOL; PROGRAM; SUPPORT; FOOD; MEETING  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A 64-year-old grandmother and a lecturer whose books on the educational plightfacing black youth have attracted national attention were featured guests at aPalo Alto luncheon May 25 to benefit the Ravenswood school district's ParentChild Intervention Program.;    The first &quot;100 Black Women Luncheon,&quot;spearheaded by Ravenswood School Superintendent Charlie Knight andco-sponsored by a local chapter of the Alpha Kappa Alpha Sorority, focused onthe triumphs of and challenges facing black families.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Peninsula Extra  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  LUNCHEON RAISES FUNDS TO AID KIDS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The luncheon, which raised $10,000 for the program through individual andcorporate donations, honored professional women on the Peninsula.;    Knightasked the women if they would like to be honored at the luncheon by donating$100 apiece to the program she created in 1989 to help the children of womenrecovering from drug abuse.;    &quot;We selected a group of women who havecontributed to their communities in a variety of ways and who are willing tofocus on the special needs of minority children and families in crisis,&quot;Knight said.;    Keynote speaker Jawanza Kunjufu, president of a Chicago-basedcommunications company, African American Images, and the author of severalbooks on black education, warned the crowd of 350 at the Palo Alto Hyatt Hotelthat black teen-agers may be the first generation ever to be less educatedthan their parents, unless parents inspire them to learn.;    &quot;These kids haveVCRs, Nintendo games and stereos in their rooms . . . and they're notinterested in studying,&quot; Kunjufu said. &quot;We're giving them lots of 'things,'but we're not giving them (our) time.&quot;;    Virginia Jackson, a mother of 10who also raised seven of her grandchildren despite multiple tragedies in herlife, was honored with the Crystal Stair Award, named for Langston Hughes'poem about perseverance in the face of adversity.;    The award honors men andwomen who step in to help a child who has been abandoned or whose family is incrisis.;    Jackson's husband died last year and, shortly after, two of herchildren were killed. However, she adopted a 6-month-old girl who wasabandoned by her mother.;    &quot;I could not go on living if I couldn't help mygrandchildren,&quot; Jackson said tearfully as she accepted her award. &quot;No matterwhat, I'm going to keep on trying.&quot;;    Knight said she was pleased with theluncheon's large turnout, especially during a holiday weekend.;    She saidshe was also encouraged by the enthusiasm of local corporations that suppliedmatching grants and helped set up the luncheon.;    &quot;The education systemneeds to be revamped and this is one of the ways the community can getinvolved,&quot; said Rose Crowder, an East Palo Alto educational consultant and oneof the &quot;100 Women.&quot;;    &quot;All the drug-exposed kids out there touch everyone'slives,&quot; Crowder said. &quot;Here's our chance to start turning that problem around.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  SUE HUTCHISON, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Peninsula/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910605  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  469  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday June 5, 199100157286,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>